entry.sense:
1. Dabava bihi, (Ṣ, Ḳ,) 
aor. _i {yaDobivu}, (Ḳ,) inf. n. DabovN, (Ṣ,) He grasped, seized, or laid hold upon, him, or it, with his hand; 
as also ADTbv↓: (Ṣ, Ḳ:) or, accord. to an explanation of the inf. n. by Ibn-Es-Seed, he did so with the utmost vehemence, or strength: (TA:) or he grasped, seized, or laid hold upon, and took, him, or it: (Sh, TA:) or Dabava Ealayohi has the first of these meanings; (A, L;) as also Dabavahu: (A:) and Dabava bihi signifies he seized him violently, or laid violent hands upon him. (A, TA.)

DabirN; 
and its n. un. DabirapN: 
see DaborN.

DiboEaAnN; 
and its fem. DiboEaAnapN: 
see DabuEN, in three places.

hom.sense:
DajaAjN a subst. from DaAj-ahu; 
[as such signifying Evil, or inimical, conduct; and contention:] (Ṣ, L, TA:) 
[and] compulsion. (Ḳ, TA.)

entry.sense:
DaHoDaAHN 
Shallow water; (Ṣ, A, TA;) and hence metaphorically applied in a trad. to ‡ a shallow part of hell-fire: (TA:) or water little in quantity; 
as also DaHoDaHN↓: or water reaching to the ankles: or reaching to the middle of the skin: or in which there is no being drowned: (Ḳ:) or water little in quantity, in a pool left by a torrent, &c. (TA.)

DaAruwrapN: 
see DararN; 
and DaruwrapN, in two places.

miDorabN 
[A thing with which one beats, strikes, smites, or hits;] a thing with which the action termed AlD-arob is performed; 
as also miDoraAbN↓. (Ḳ.) A wooden instrument [a kind of mallet] with which the bow-string is struck in the operation of separating cotton. (Mṣb.)

hom.sense:
Darasatohu AlxuTuwbu, 
inf. n. DarosN, ‡ Things or affairs, or calamities, tried, or tested, him; 
as also Dr-sthu↓. (TA.)

Also ‡ A man who has been tried, or proved, or tried and strengthened, by experience; (A, TA;) whom trials have befallen, as though he had been bitten thereby: (TA:) who has been tried, or proved, and rendered expert, or strong, by wars, (Ṣ, A,) and by affairs, or calamities: (A:) like munaj-acN from naAjicN: (A, TA:) or who has become experienced in affairs: (AA, Ṣ:) one who has travelled, and become experienced in affairs, and fought; 
as also DirosN↓ 
and DarisN↓. (TA.)

entry.sense:
And Darima Ealayohi (Mṣb,* Ḳ) ‡ His anger became violent [against him]: (Mṣb:) or he burned with anger against him; 
as also tDr-m↓ Elyh; (Ḳ;) or the latter signifies he became angered against him: (Ṣ, TA:) 


and ADTrm↓ Elyh he was, or became, angry with him. (TA.)

DaginN 
Affected with rancour, malevolence, malice, or spite; 
as also DaAginN↓. (Mṣb.)

Also † A piece of stick or wood; syn. EuwdN; 
[erroneously supposed by Golius and Freytag to mean here the musical instrument thus called;] (IAạr, O, Ḳ;) so in a saying of the Prophet to a woman, respecting a blood-stain on a garment, Hut-iyhi biDilaEK 
† [Scrape thou it off with a piece of stick]: (IAạr, O:) or † such as is wide and curved; as being likened to the DilaE (O, Ḳ) of an animal. (Ḳ.)

DamoDamN A lion that grasps everything; 
as also DumaADimN↓. (Ṣ.) 
[See also DamoDaAmN: and see what here follows.]

He prepared him (i. e. a horse) for racing, [or for a military expedition, 
(see muDam-irN,)] 
by feeding him with food barely sufficient to sustain him, after he had become fat; 
as also ADmrhu↓. (Mṣb:) he fed him with food barely sufficient to sustain him, after he had become fat; 
as also ADmrhu↓: (Ḳ:) or he fed him with fodder so that he became fat, and then reduced him to food barely sufficient to sustain him; which is done during forty days: (Ṣ:) or he saddled him, and put on him a housing, in order that he might sweat under it, and so lose his flabbiness, and become firm in flesh; and then mounted upon him a light boy or young man, to make him run, but not to make him go so quick a pace as that which is termed Eanaq; by the doing of which, one becomes in no fear of his losing his breath in running, and a quick run does not cut him short: this (says AM) is what I have seen the Arabs practise; and they term it taDomiyrN, 
and also miDomaArN↓. (T, L.)

Din-apN 
an inf. n. of Dan-a: (Mṣb:) or a subst. therefrom signifying Niggardliness, tenaciousness, stinginess, or avarice: (Mgh:) or vehement niggardliness, &c.; 
as also maDan-apN↓. (TA.)

DaniynapN; 
and its pl. DanaAYinu: 
see Din-N.

DanK; 
fem. DaniyapN; 
and pl. OaDonaMCN: 
see the next preceding paragraph, in three places.

muDonFI 
Rendered lean, or emaciated; 
[&c;] (Mgh;) pass. part. n. of 4 [q. v.]. (Mgh, Mṣb.)

hom.sense:
DahoyaON, of the measure faEolalN, or, as some say, faEoyalN; if of the latter, [said to be] the only instance of this measure in the language; 


DahoyadN being a foreign proper name; (TA;) or, maroyamu being a foreign proper name; (TA;) or, accord. to Sb, the hemzeh in DahoyaON, which is with tenween, is augmentative, because it is syn. with DahoyaMCu, which is with the long A and imperfectly decl., for the I cannot be augmentative and the hemzeh radical in the latter; (MF and TA in art. DhI;) [a word like DahoyFA and DahoyaMCu 
(which see in art. DhI) in most, or a some seem to say in all, of its meanings;] A certain tree, resembling the sayaAl, (AZ, O, Ḳ,) each of which has its fruit in a sinofap [or pod]; it has weak thorns, and grows in the valleys and on the mountains: (AZ, O:) Ed-Deenawaree [i. e. AḤn] says, on the authority of some one or more of the Arabs of the desert, of El-Azd, that the DhyO is a great tree of the kind called EiDaAh, having a baramap [q. v.] and a pod (Eul--afap) [which succeeds the baramap], and many thorns; its pods (Eul-af) are intensely red, and its leaves are like those of the [species of acacia called] samur. (O.)

entry.sense:
muDawoDK A man crying out; shouting, or clamouring; 
(Ḳ and TA in art. DwD; [in the CK erroneously written muDawoDiI-;]) 
like muDawoDiYN. (TA in that art.)

1. DawonapN, (Ḳ,) an inf. n. of which the verb is DaAna, aor. yaDuwnu, said of a man, (TḲ,) The having numerous offspring; 
as also taDaw-unN↓. (Ḳ.) 
[Probably from DayowanN.]

hom.sense:
And DAf said of a man, † He feared; 
as also ADAf↓. (M.) 
And ADAf↓ minohu † He feared it, or was cautious of it; namely, an event, or affair; (Ṣ, M, O, Ḳ, TA;) as also DAf minohu: (TA:) or ‡ he was cautious of it with the caution of one encompassed, or beset, thereby. (Z, TA.)

And Difotuhu signifies also I sought, or desired, of him entertainment as a Dayof [or guest]; 
and so taDay-afotuhu↓; (M;) or this latter, (L, Mṣb,) 
and AisotaDafotuhu↓, (M,) I asked of him such entertainment. (M, L, Mṣb.)

